2026-01-23 14:25:44,883 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-dda3a634-d434-4bcd-935d-77b748d9708e', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Somos naturaleza. Una experiencia audiovisual inmersiva, Exhibition, CaixaForum Madrid, Madrid\n- Venue: CaixaForum Madrid\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: CaixaForum Madrid, Paseo del Prado, 36, 28014 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-06-18 to 2027-03-07\n- Suggested visit duration: 70 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Labels at CaixaForum Madrid keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'See\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "See immersive projections and specimen cases trace ecosystems and extraction at CaixaForum Madrid in about 70 minutes.", "long": "<p>Labels at CaixaForum Madrid keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft.</p>\\n<p>Running in Madrid from 18 June 2026 to 7 March 2027, Somos naturaleza unfolds as a 70 minute circuit through dark projection rooms, sound corridors and study tables. The route moves from cellular forms to watersheds and forests, then turns to mining, transport and waste. Text panels stay specific, naming materials, scales and recording methods, so each claim sits beside a trace or a tool rather than a slogan. Light cues and bass pulses mark transitions, keeping the sequence continuous even when the mood shifts from wonder to abrasion.</p>\\n<p>Highlight: a full-room, 360 degree projection chamber tracks seasonal change across coast, wetland and dry plains, while spatial audio drives wind, insect swarm and distant thunder around the body. One don’t-miss element is the narrow transition corridor where clean field recordings (rain on leaves, seabirds, cicadas) cut hard into industrial hum and engine rumble, turning the seam between habitat and city into a physical jolt. Another don’t-miss is the data wall that converts temperature and rainfall records into stacked colour bands, letting decades thicken, thin and fracture in real time beside a running timestamp.</p>\\n<p>Object cases anchor the immersion with compact, legible evidence. Herbarium sheets, seed pods and pressed leaves sit beside microscope slides of pollen grains and fungal spores. Tree-ring cores read as drought and recovery lines, while drawers of pinned insects compress scale and diversity into a single glance. Air-quality filter strips and sediment jars sit next to magnified plastic pellets, tying the sound and image sequences to lungs, rivers and food chains. Field notebooks and survey cards keep the focus on method, with repeated counts, margin corrections and clipped maps.</p>\\n<p>Hidden gem: a quiet listening nook loops underwater hydrophone recordings, where shrimp clicks and whale calls compete with propellers and sonar pings, a tight lesson in acoustic ecology. In the final rooms, short films and pared-back diagrams trace supply chains and land-use shifts, then loop back to earlier specimens so cause and consequence share the same sightline. Sound levels swing sharply between spaces, and benches in the darkest rooms support a slower pass through the densest edits. A small monitor logs decibel readings per soundscape, setting numbers beside sensation.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
