2026-01-23 14:26:05,609 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-e3492c83-67d6-4440-90c7-a896f4e611ab', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Robert Capa. ICONS, Círculo de Bellas Artes, Madrid\n- Venue: Círculo de Bellas Artes\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Círculo de Bellas Artes, C/ Alcalá, 42, 28014 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2025-10-02 to 2026-01-25\n- Suggested visit duration: 90 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Inside the galleries at Círculo de Bellas Artes, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Compare\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Compare wartime negatives with magazine spreads and contact sheets, tracing how photojournalism images become icons in Madrid.", "long": "<p>Inside the galleries at Círculo de Bellas Artes, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context. Prints, contact sheets and editorial layouts sit side by side, so the shift from urgent capture to public image stays visible. Wall texts keep dates and places tight, while quieter vitrines hold working tools that anchor the photographs in daily practice.</p>\\n<p>The opening rooms focus on the Spanish Civil War and the ethics of proximity. A highlight is The Falling Soldier (Cerro Muriano, 1936), presented with surrounding frames that emphasise sequencing rather than a single decisive moment. In Madrid, that section lands with particular force, as bombed streets, militia drills and civilian flight read as documentary record rather than distant history. Do not miss the pairing of battlefield photographs with press captions that reveal how meaning changes in print.</p>\\n<p>World War II drives the pace up, with images made under pressure and often under restriction. The blurred, salt-stained D-Day photographs from Omaha Beach (6 June 1944) form one of the most direct encounters with danger and mechanical limits. Do not miss the contact sheets that keep rejected frames in view, including crop marks and grease-pencil edits that show decisions at the desk as clearly as decisions in the field. A run of magazine spreads from Life and Picture Post tracks the same images as they circulate.</p>\\n<p>Paris reappears in scenes from the Liberation (August 1944), where crowds, uniforms and street corners replace trenches, and the photographer’s attention shifts to faces and gestures. Later rooms widen into post-war assignments and friendships, including Pablo Picasso at the beach in Golfe-Juan (1948), where fame reads as informal, even awkward, under direct flash and midday sun.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem is the small group of colour transparencies and lesser-known portraits, hung with restraint to keep looking slow. The final section touches on the founding of Magnum Photos in 1947 and the ongoing afterlife of the archive, including stamps, annotations and publication notes that complicate the idea of a single “icon”. On view at Círculo de Bellas Artes in Madrid, Spain, from 2 October 2025 to 25 January 2026, with a suggested visit duration of 90 minutes.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
