2026-01-23 14:26:41,638 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-11476a02-17f7-4a24-8780-799522615479', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: ¡Aquí hay petróleo!, Círculo de Bellas Artes, Madrid\n- Venue: Círculo de Bellas Artes\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Círculo de Bellas Artes, C/ Alcalá, 42, 28014 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2025-11-07 to 2026-02-08\n- Suggested visit duration: 60 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Inside the galleries at Círculo de Bellas Artes, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Compare\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Compare drilling dreams and propaganda in Madrid through maps, posters and newsreels, and trace how oil shapes politics, labour and daily routines.", "long": "<p>Inside the galleries at Círculo de Bellas Artes, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context. Set in Madrid, Spain, ¡Aquí hay petróleo! tracks the search for crude oil as a scientific project, an industrial wager and a political narrative, then follows the consequences through work sites, households and the press. The pacing suits a 60 minute visit, with clear signposting between research, extraction and representation.</p>\\n<p>The opening rooms focus on evidence and persuasion. A highlight is a wall-sized geological map marked with drill targets and hand-inked revisions, the kind of working document that turns speculation into policy. Nearby, seismic survey diagrams and stratigraphic columns translate subterranean layers into lines and numbers, while telegrams and memoranda show how quickly uncertainty hardens into orders.</p>\\n<p>Don’t miss the run of CAMPSA advertising posters, where tankers, refineries and pump attendants become tools of reassurance. Typography and colour do the heavy lifting, promising stability while masking scarcity and dependency. Another don’t-miss element is the NO-DO newsreel montage: staged ribbon-cuttings, choreographed machinery and carefully framed crowds, edited into a single loop that makes extraction look inevitable.</p>\\n<p>Material from the oil field at Ayoluengo (La Lora) grounds the narrative in physical matter. A labelled core sample and drilling fragments sit beside shift schedules and safety notices, pulling attention from slogans to routine labour. Photographs of rigs at dusk, canteens and temporary barracks tighten the focus on logistics, fatigue and the social life built around the wellhead.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem appears in a small case of field paperwork: a geologist’s notebook packed with quick sketches, depth figures and weather notes, smudged at the edges from handling. Press clippings and parliamentary extracts around it reveal how the same data travels upward, first as technical language, then as headlines and talking points. On view from 7 November 2025 to 8 February 2026 at Círculo de Bellas Artes, the display keeps returning to the gap between what the ground contains and what institutions claim it contains.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 329)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
