2026-01-23 14:27:25,803 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-716b1d1a-6810-4f4c-998e-f54c40cfec96', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: ¡Aquí hay petróleo!, Círculo de Bellas Artes, Madrid\n- Venue: Círculo de Bellas Artes\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Círculo de Bellas Artes, C/ Alcalá, 42, 28014 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2025-11-07 to 2026-02-08\n- Suggested visit duration: 60 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Inside the galleries at Círculo de Bellas Artes, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Compare\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Compare drilling dreams and propaganda through maps, posters and newsreels, tracing how oil shapes politics, labour and daily routines.", "long": "<p>Inside the galleries at Círculo de Bellas Artes, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context. ¡Aquí hay petróleo! follows the hunt for crude oil as science, industry and state messaging, then tracks what that hunt does to work, transport and domestic life. The route reads clearly in about 60 minutes, with tight transitions from survey to extraction to public image.</p>\\n<p>The opening rooms insist on measurement before myth. A highlight is a wall-sized geological map, crowded with drill targets, hand-inked corrections and pencilled depth notes that turn uncertainty into a plan. Nearby, seismic survey diagrams and stratigraphic columns compress kilometres of rock into clean lines, while telegrams, permits and typed memoranda reveal how quickly technical language becomes administrative instruction. A small display of sample vials and sand trays links those abstractions back to grit, weight and colour.</p>\\n<p>Don’t miss the run of CAMPSA advertising posters, where tankers, refinery stacks and pump attendants deliver reassurance through hard geometry, limited palettes and blunt slogans. The posters sit beside price lists and ration notices, forcing a comparison between promise and procurement. Another don’t-miss element is the NO-DO newsreel montage: choreographed machinery, staged inaugurations and tidy crowds, cut into a loop that makes extraction feel orderly and inevitable. The editing rhythm matters as much as the images, turning drills and pipelines into a national routine.</p>\\n<p>Material from the Ayoluengo well in La Lora grounds the story in labour and maintenance. A labelled core sample and worn drill fragments sit alongside shift rosters, safety notices and canteen rules, pulling attention from rhetoric to daily risk. Photographs of rigs at dusk, temporary barracks and muddy access roads tighten the focus on logistics, fatigue and the social world built around a single wellhead.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem waits in a narrow case of field paperwork: a geologist’s pocket notebook packed with quick section sketches, depth figures and weather notes, the paper edges darkened by repeated handling. Press clippings and parliamentary extracts nearby show the same data travelling upward, first as cautious technical phrasing and then as certainty. On view from 7 November 2025 to 8 February 2026, the final wall pairs import statistics with household receipts for paraffin and petrol.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
