2026-01-23 14:28:33,874 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-a3e1a410-3dd4-4f84-bda0-ae7d3468d211', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Eclosión. El Círculo de Bellas Artes en los 80 y 90, Círculo de Bellas Artes, Madrid\n- Venue: Círculo de Bellas Artes\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Círculo de Bellas Artes, C/ Alcalá, 42, 28014 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-02-25 to 2026-05-10\n- Suggested visit duration: 60 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: In the first rooms at Círculo de Bellas Artes, close looking matters as objects and images do the work.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Meet\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Meet Madrid’s 80s and 90s creative surge, trace posters, photos and fanzines, and sense how Círculo de Bellas Artes fuelled the city.", "long": "<p>In the first rooms at Círculo de Bellas Artes, close looking matters as objects and images do the work. Paper yellows, staples rust, ink bleeds, and the city’s cultural machinery comes into view through invitations, programmes, press clippings and rehearsal notes. The route maps how the institution hosted and provoked experimentation across art, music, cinema and publishing in Madrid during the 1980s and 1990s.</p>\\n<p>A key highlight is the dense wall of posters and handbills, where type, photocopy grain and quick collage announce concerts, readings and late sessions, often with tear-off tabs still intact. Nearby, design studies and mock-ups reveal how a single event moved from sketch to print run. The selection makes room for rough, working objects, stapled fanzines, annotated timetables, and staff memos that carry the pace of production.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements anchor the visual story. First, photographs by Alberto García-Alix, where stark black-and-white portraits pin down faces and gestures without smoothing them into myth. Second, colour images by Ouka Leele, where staged lighting and saturated tones turn ordinary rooms into charged sets. Works on paper by Ceesepe appear alongside magazine spreads and contact sheets, allowing drawing, publication and nightlife to sit on the same plane.</p>\\n<p>The exhibition keeps turning towards the building itself, including material from performances and debates held in its halls, plus documentation of collaborations with musicians, filmmakers and small presses. A listening area threads sound through the display, with recordings tied to specific nights and series. The suggested visit duration is 60 minutes, enough to read captions, compare print variants and track recurring names across decades.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits in the quieter archival section, a small cluster of handwritten correspondence and marked-up layouts that show decisions midstream, with crossings-out and last-minute additions still visible. Between 25 February and 10 May 2026, the galleries hold this accumulation of drafts, proofs and finished works in Madrid, Spain.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 312)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
