2026-01-23 14:29:40,390 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-a45b9adc-c09f-44f3-baa0-fe5b114873e6', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Eclosión. El Círculo de Bellas Artes en los 80 y 90, Círculo de Bellas Artes, Madrid\n- Venue: Círculo de Bellas Artes\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Círculo de Bellas Artes, C/ Alcalá, 42, 28014 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-02-25 to 2026-05-10\n- Suggested visit duration: 60 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: In the first rooms at Círculo de Bellas Artes, close looking matters as objects and images do the work.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Meet\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Meet Madrid’s 80s and 90s creative surge, read fanzines and posters, and hear recordings from nights that shaped Círculo de Bellas Artes.", "long": "<p>In the first rooms at Círculo de Bellas Artes, close looking matters as objects and images do the work. Paper yellows, staples rust, ink bleeds, and the city’s cultural machinery comes into view through invitations, programmes, press clippings and rehearsal notes. Open since 25 February 2026 and continuing until 10 May 2026, the display follows how the institution acts as stage, noticeboard and meeting point for Madrid’s creative networks across the 1980s and 1990s.</p>\\n<p>A clear highlight is the packed wall of posters and handbills, pinned edge to edge so typography, photocopy grain and quick collage stay legible. Some sheets carry pricing, phone numbers, and the scuffed marks of being taped up and torn down. Nearby, rough mock-ups, printer’s proofs and corrected layouts show how one night’s event moves from sketch to print run, with crossing-outs and hurried notes still intact.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements sharpen the human story. First, photographs by Alberto García-Alix, where hard-edged black and white portraits hold bodies, jewellery and leather with unsentimental clarity. Second, colour images by Ouka Leele, where staged scenes and saturated tones turn bedrooms, rooftops and streets into charged sets. Drawings by Ceesepe appear in dialogue with magazine spreads and contact sheets, keeping illustration, publication and nightlife on the same plane.</p>\\n<p>The route keeps circling back to the building’s own rooms and rhythms. Documentation of performances, debates and screenings sits beside internal paperwork, including schedules, staff memos and annotated running orders. A listening area threads sound through the archive, pairing recordings with dates and series titles rather than nostalgia, while film stills and press cuttings show how word of mouth turns into headlines. A 60 minute circuit leaves time to read captions, compare print variants and track recurring names.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem waits in the quieter archival section, a small set of meeting minutes and budget sheets, where decisions about fees, equipment and last-minute substitutions sit beside doodles in the margins. Postcards, stamped envelopes and handwritten notes of thanks keep the tone intimate, even when the subjects are public events. Small details, a torn ticket stub, a coffee-ringed timetable, a corrected caption, keep reappearing from case to case.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
