2026-01-23 14:29:51,459 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-24519330-469d-40f1-965d-55e8bc264065', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: La lechuza de Minerva, Círculo de Bellas Artes, Madrid\n- Venue: Círculo de Bellas Artes\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Círculo de Bellas Artes, C/ Alcalá, 42, 28014 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-03-04 to 2026-05-10\n- Suggested visit duration: 60 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Rooms at Círculo de Bellas Artes map the show’s themes through objects, images, sound and text.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Chart\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Chart the owl’s flight from Hegel to contemporary sound, with books, prints and nocturnal rooms at Círculo de Bellas Artes.", "long": "<p>Rooms at Círculo de Bellas Artes map the show’s themes through objects, images, sound and text. In Madrid, La lechuza de Minerva takes Hegel’s famous image of wisdom arriving at dusk and tests it against art, politics and everyday experience. The route moves from classical symbols to modern crises, keeping the owl as a recurring sign across media rather than a single mascot. Each section tightens the question of what can be understood only after events have already unfolded.</p>\\n<p>The opening section anchors the metaphor in material culture. An Athenian owl coin (presented as a replica) sits beside studies of Athena, alongside prints and diagrams that track how the bird shifts from civic emblem to philosophical shorthand. Nearby, small cases pair natural history notes with superstitions from popular song and printed broadsides, keeping the image tethered to hands, pockets and streets. A highlight comes in a compact “dusk room” where light levels drop, wall texts compress into aphorisms, and a low soundtrack of evening field recordings reframes the gallery as a threshold between action and reflection.</p>\\n<p>On paper, the argument sharpens. Editions of Hegel’s Phenomenology of Spirit and Philosophy of Right sit near counterpoints by Walter Benjamin (Theses on the Philosophy of History) and María Zambrano (Claros del bosque), letting opposed ideas share the same table. Marginalia and editorial notes steer attention to how concepts harden, then crack, under pressure. Two do not miss elements stand out: the projected sequence of Francisco de Goya’s Los Caprichos, including The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters, and a graphic timeline that stitches together revolutions, strikes and student movements with changing images of the owl in newspapers and posters.</p>\\n<p>Image-making pushes the theme into unease. Albrecht Dürer’s Melencolia I appears in large-scale reproduction with annotations that pick apart tools, shadows and the stalled body, while a nearby wall of contemporary photo-essays follows night work, surveillance cameras and lit windows across the city. The sound layer never retreats into background, it cuts, loops and interrupts reading, forcing choices about pace and attention. A cluster of short texts on laws, pamphlets and headlines keeps the political thread close to the artwork.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits in a small study alcove: a drawer of facsimile notebooks filled with crossings-out, underlinings and rewritten quotations, as if thinking itself were an object with weight and friction. The exhibition runs from 4 March to 10 May 2026 at Círculo de Bellas Artes in Madrid, and a clear circuit suits a 60 minute visit. The alcove stays quiet even when the main rooms thicken with sound, so the pencil marks read as deliberate acts rather than decoration.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 436)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
