2026-01-23 14:30:07,962 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-f0ee6a2b-e7df-4474-99a7-627f220286aa', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: La lechuza de Minerva, Círculo de Bellas Artes, Madrid\n- Venue: Círculo de Bellas Artes\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Círculo de Bellas Artes, C/ Alcalá, 42, 28014 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-03-04 to 2026-05-10\n- Suggested visit duration: 60 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Rooms at Círculo de Bellas Artes map the show’s themes through objects, images, sound and text.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Chart\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Chart the owl’s flight from Hegel to nocturnal sound, with prints, books and dimmed rooms at Círculo de Bellas Artes.", "long": "<p>Rooms at Círculo de Bellas Artes map the show’s themes through objects, images, sound and text. In Madrid, the guiding motif is Hegel’s owl of Minerva, a figure for wisdom that arrives at dusk, after events have taken their course. The route treats the owl as a migrating sign, moving between civic emblem, superstition, philosophical shorthand and political warning. Labels keep close to concrete things, coins, paper, ink, light, and the habits of reading at night.</p>\\n<p>The opening galleries anchor the symbol in material culture. An Athenian owl coin (replica) sits beside studies of Athena and diagrams charting the bird’s shift from city icon to idea. Nearby, broadsides and song sheets pin the owl to street life and domestic fear, while natural history notes insist on feathers, talons and hunting. A highlight comes in a compact “dusk room” where the lighting drops, wall texts compress into aphorisms, and a looping track of evening field recordings turns the act of looking into a slowed, attentive practice.</p>\\n<p>On paper, the argument tightens. Editions of Hegel’s Phenomenology of Spirit and Philosophy of Right share a table with counterpoints by Walter Benjamin (Theses on the Philosophy of History) and María Zambrano (Claros del bosque). Marginalia, editorial apparatus and selected quotations make thinking look like labour. Two don’t miss elements stand out: a projected sequence from Francisco de Goya’s Los Caprichos, including The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters, and a graphic timeline that threads revolutions, strikes and student movements through shifting owl imagery in newspapers, posters and pamphlets.</p>\\n<p>Image-making pushes the theme into unease. Albrecht Dürer’s Melencolia I appears as a large reproduction with annotations that pick apart tools, shadows and a stalled body. A nearby wall of contemporary photo essays tracks night work, surveillance cameras and lit windows across the city, keeping the political thread close to the everyday. The sound layer cuts and interrupts rather than settling into background, pressing decisions about pace, attention and silence.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits in a small study alcove: a drawer of facsimile notebooks filled with crossings-out, underlinings and rewritten quotations, as if thought has weight and friction. Running from 4 March to 10 May 2026, the circuit suits a 60 minute visit, with the alcove staying notably quiet as other rooms thicken with audio loops.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
