2026-01-23 14:31:28,779 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-b0c384e2-7059-4dba-9359-932e50596d79', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Anders Zorn. Recorrer el mundo, recordar la tierra, Exhibition, Fundación MAPFRE (Sala Recoletos), Madrid\n- Venue: Fundación MAPFRE (Sala Recoletos)\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Fundación MAPFRE (Sala Recoletos), Paseo de Recoletos, 23, 28004 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-02-19 to 2026-05-17\n- Suggested visit duration: 90 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Across the galleries at Fundación MAPFRE (Sala Recoletos), materials and techniques carry the argument without hype.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Compare\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Compare Zorn’s etchings, portraits and travel watercolours, then follow how distant journeys loop back to Swedish soil.", "long": "<p>Across the galleries at Fundación MAPFRE (Sala Recoletos), materials and techniques carry the argument without hype. Anders Zorn moves between oil paint, watercolour and etching with the same sharp eye for light on skin, snow and water, and the same appetite for movement in a room. Born in 1860 in Mora, he travels widely, yet keeps returning to Dalarna as both subject and touchstone. The display runs from 19 February to 17 May 2026 and rewards an unhurried 90 minutes.</p>\\n<p>The opening rooms set travel against homecoming. Quick watercolours and sketch studies record ports, streets and interiors with economical marks, then swing back to the restrained tones of Sweden. Among the anchor works, <i>Midsummer Dance (Midsommardans)</i> presses bodies into a tight circle, the brushwork turning music into torque and dust into atmosphere. A second key stop, <i>Mona</i>, holds a sitter in steady light, with a face built from confident planes rather than softening effects, and the hands described with decisive edges.</p>\\n<p>Highlight, the etching section: black ink, white paper, and a draughtsman’s control of greys. Don’t miss the chance to track how Zorn shifts from velvety shadow to razor line across a sequence of plates, including <i>Self-Portrait</i>, where the artist’s gaze sits under brisk, unsentimental modelling. Another don’t-miss element is the close pairing of preparatory drawings with finished works, which makes revisions and bold deletions plain, and shows how a contour is tightened or abandoned once the pose settles.</p>\\n<p>Portraiture carries social and psychological weight. In <i>The Omnibus</i>, faces and hats crowd a shared public space, and the composition choreographs glances rather than offering a posed tableau. Elsewhere, studies of hands, cuffs and jewellery insist on touch and pressure, from starched fabric to polished metal, with each change of surface handled by a change of stroke and a change of paint load.</p>\\n<p>Hidden gem, a small cluster of intimate material, letters, photographs and sketchbook pages, sits quietly between larger canvases and opens the working routine behind the public commissions. It makes room for marginal notes on colour, thumbnail diagrams of compositions, and the way a travel impression reappears later as a remembered shoreline, shifted into a different season and light.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
