2026-01-23 14:31:30,644 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-60fb4db9-2d06-4ae1-b2d5-570fbe6ac4a5', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Exposición “NIKE. DISEÑO EN MOVIMIENTO”, TeamLabs Madrid, Madrid\n- Venue: TeamLabs Madrid\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: TeamLabs Madrid, Plaza de San Martín, 1 (Entrada por la calle Hileras, 18), 28013 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2025-11-12 to 2026-01-25\n- Suggested visit duration: 60 to 90 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Rooms at TeamLabs Madrid map the show’s themes through objects, images, sound and text.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Chart\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Chart how the Swoosh reshapes running and basketball shoes, from waffle soles to Vaporfly prototypes, at TeamLabs Madrid.", "long": "<p>Rooms at TeamLabs Madrid map the show’s themes through objects, images, sound and text. In Madrid, the route traces how a global sports brand turns research, athlete feedback and factory craft into shoes and apparel that change how bodies move. The exhibition runs from 12 November 2025 to 25 January 2026.</p>\\n<p>Early sections follow experimentation in rubber, foam and stitching, with a Waffle Trainer sole prototype beside material swatches and manufacturing tools. A hidden gem sits in a small vitrine: a battered kitchen waffle iron, credited to Bill Bowerman’s first outsole trials, shown alongside a test mould and a set of hand cut tread samples.</p>\\n<p>Do not miss the design wall dedicated to Air Max 1 (1987), including Tinker Hatfield’s pencil sketches and a cutaway showing the visible Air unit. Nearby, Air Jordan 1 (1985) anchors a chapter on basketball identity and colour rules, pairing an original black and red pair with archival photography that tracks its leap from court kit to street uniform.</p>\\n<p>A central gallery shifts to performance engineering. Do not miss the Vaporfly 4% prototype display, presented with carbon plate cross sections, midsole foam blocks and a timeline of record breaking race results. Interactive audio stations unpack testing language, cadence, impact and energy return, while motion clips compare stride mechanics across distances.</p>\\n<p>A highlight is the Flyknit workshop zone, where knitted uppers hang like pattern maps, showing tension changes, yarn types and seam reduction. Sample panels invite close reading of stitch density and reinforcement placement, and a colour library ties digital design files to finished uppers in training and competition palettes.</p>\\n<p>The final rooms track collaborations and cultural adoption through campaign stills, limited run releases and athlete issued objects, including signed spikes and training notes. TeamLabs Madrid keeps the route compact and legible, with clear captions in Spanish and English. Suggested visit duration is 60 to 90 minutes.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 311)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
