2026-01-23 14:31:56,583 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-2bf54d72-0fde-4b50-bf3c-e0d767805842', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Anders Zorn. Recorrer el mundo, recordar la tierra, Exhibition, Fundación MAPFRE (Sala Recoletos), Madrid\n- Venue: Fundación MAPFRE (Sala Recoletos)\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Fundación MAPFRE (Sala Recoletos), Paseo de Recoletos, 23, 28004 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-02-19 to 2026-05-17\n- Suggested visit duration: 90 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Across the galleries at Fundación MAPFRE (Sala Recoletos), materials and techniques carry the argument without hype.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Compare\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Compare Zorn’s etchings, portraits and travel watercolours, then trace how distant journeys circle back to Swedish soil.", "long": "<p>Across the galleries at Fundación MAPFRE (Sala Recoletos), materials and techniques carry the argument without hype. Anders Zorn moves between oil paint, watercolour and etching with a hard-earned grasp of light on skin, snow and water. Born in 1860 in Mora, he travels widely, yet keeps returning to Dalarna as subject and measure of truth. The display runs from 19 February to 17 May 2026 and suits an unhurried 90 minutes.</p>\\n<p>The opening section sets mobility against rootedness. Quick watercolours and sketch studies record streets, boats and interiors with economical marks, then give way to Swedish scenes tightened by colder tones. One early anchor, <i>Midsummer Dance (Midsommardans)</i>, drives bodies into a rotating ring, brushwork turning music into torque and dust into atmosphere. Another key stop, <i>Mona</i>, holds a sitter in steady light, face built from confident planes and hands described with decisive edges rather than softening effects.</p>\\n<p>Highlight, the etching rooms: black ink, white paper, and control over greys that never turns mannered. Don’t miss the run of plates that shows Zorn shifting from velvety shadow to razor line, including <i>Self-Portrait</i>, where the gaze sits under brisk, unsentimental modelling. Don’t miss, too, the tight pairing of preparatory drawings with finished works, which makes revisions plain and shows how a contour is cut back once the pose settles.</p>\\n<p>Portraiture carries social weight as well as craft. In <i>The Omnibus</i>, faces and hats crowd a shared public space, composition choreographing glances rather than presenting a posed tableau. Elsewhere, studies of hands, cuffs and jewellery insist on touch and pressure, from starched fabric to polished metal, each surface answered by a change of stroke and paint load.</p>\\n<p>Hidden gem, a small cluster of intimate material, letters, photographs and sketchbook pages, sits quietly between larger canvases and shifts attention to working routine and revision. Marginal notes on colour, thumbnail diagrams, and crossed-out passages show decisions made under time pressure, then re-used later when a travel impression returns as a remembered shoreline in a different season and light.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 337)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
