2026-01-23 14:32:02,029 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-96ce03bf-2d34-41ea-90c5-8e1df2c2ffee', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Exposición “NIKE. DISEÑO EN MOVIMIENTO”, TeamLabs Madrid, Madrid\n- Venue: TeamLabs Madrid\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: TeamLabs Madrid, Plaza de San Martín, 1 (Entrada por la calle Hileras, 18), 28013 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2025-11-12 to 2026-01-25\n- Suggested visit duration: 60 to 90 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Rooms at TeamLabs Madrid map the show’s themes through objects, images, sound and text.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Chart\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Chart how the Swoosh reshapes running and basketball shoes, from waffle soles to Vaporfly prototypes, at TeamLabs Madrid.", "long": "<p>Rooms at TeamLabs Madrid map the show’s themes through objects, images, sound and text. In Madrid, the route tracks how Nike turns lab testing, athlete feedback and factory craft into shoes and apparel that change movement. On view from 12 November 2025 to 25 January 2026, it keeps attention on process rather than myth, with crisp captions in Spanish and English.</p>\\n<p>Early rooms dig into trial-and-error material work, pairing rubber compounds, foam cores and stitching samples with a Waffle Trainer outsole prototype. A hidden gem sits in a small vitrine: a scuffed kitchen waffle iron linked to Bill Bowerman’s first tread experiments, set beside a test mould, hand-cut lug strips and annotated notes on traction and wear.</p>\\n<p>Do not miss the section on Air as an engineered object. An Air Max 1 (1987) display brings together Tinker Hatfield’s pencil sketches, a cutaway midsole that exposes the visible Air unit and production tooling that explains how the window survives impact. Nearby, a graphic chapter credits Carolyn Davidson’s 1971 Swoosh drawings, then follows the mark across tongue labels, heel tabs and box graphics.</p>\\n<p>Another do not miss element is the performance corridor centred on the Vaporfly 4% prototype. Carbon plate cross-sections, Pebax foam blocks and stacked sample midsoles sit alongside race documentation and slow-motion gait clips that compare cadence and ground contact. Close by, Nike Free tooling studies and early Shox columns underline how cushioning concepts swing between flexibility and mechanical rebound.</p>\\n<p>A highlight comes in the Flyknit zone, where uppers hang like pattern maps and reveal tension shifts, yarn types and seam reduction. Stitch-density swatches show reinforcement placement around toe, midfoot and heel, while a colour library ties digital knit files to finished uppers across training and competition palettes.</p>\\n<p>Later rooms turn to collaborations and cultural adoption through campaign stills, limited-run releases and athlete-issued objects, including signed spikes, training logs and taped-up laces. A small wall of repair and wear, re-glued soles, frayed eyelets and marked insoles, keeps the focus on use as evidence. Allow 60 to 90 minutes.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 338)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
