2026-01-23 14:33:40,306 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-1107d1df-ff10-4e2e-aa83-0b70a5f8fd5f', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Exposición, Exhibition, Cosentino City Madrid, Madrid\n- Venue: Cosentino City Madrid\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Cosentino City Madrid, Paseo de la Castellana, 116, 28046 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-02-19 to 2026-03-08\n- Suggested visit duration: 45 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Inside the galleries at Cosentino City Madrid, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Track\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Track material studies at Cosentino City Madrid, compare matte and polished planes, and test edge profiles and joins in 45 minutes.", "long": "<p>Inside the galleries at Cosentino City Madrid, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context. Running from 19 February to 8 March 2026, it keeps the pace brisk, shifting between room-scale surfaces and hand-scale evidence of how they were made. Open sightlines let reflections and joins read from across the room before the route tightens into close looking.</p>\\n<p>At the centre is a sequence of full-height panels in engineered stone and ultra-compact surfaces, hung so thickness, edge choices and fixing points remain legible. Labels stay practical, listing cut directions, polishing stages, sealants and tolerance notes. A narrow table carries offcuts, drill tests and corner mitres, each marked with pencil measurements that mirror the wall labels, turning specification into something tangible.</p>\\n<p>Highlight: the room-scale slab installation <i>City Grid</i> sets alternating matte and polished planes into a strict rhythm, so light shifts with each pass and the grid seems to pulse without any mechanics. Beside it, <i>Counterpoint</i> compresses tessellated samples into a single long plane, where changes in grain, reflectivity and undertone reveal themselves under constant lighting. A third anchor work, <i>Seam Study</i>, isolates three joint types on identical surfaces to make alignment and filler colour easy to judge.</p>\\n<p>Don’t miss element one: the process wall of annotated CAD prints, taped mock-ups and rejected revisions, pinned beside the finished panels they describe, with crossings-out left in place. The edits make material decisions readable, from seam placement to the final edge radius. Don’t miss element two: <i>Cut Line</i>, a short documentary photo series by Madrid photographer Lucía García, tracking water-jet cuts, edge profiling, dry fits and sealing, with timestamps that align to objects on display.</p>\\n<p>Hidden gem: a low drawer unit labelled “Failures” holds cracked corners, scorched test strips and misaligned joins, each tagged with the adjustment that followed and the tool that caused the error. A compact reading table gathers spec sheets, swatch cards, adhesive samples and an “Edge Library” of finished profiles (bullnose, bevel and pencil) set beside a single lamp for controlled light. Suggested visit duration is 45 minutes, with a shorter loop possible by skipping the reading table and returning later for the drawers.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
