2026-01-23 14:34:41,909 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-01ae1c48-78bb-4bcc-a248-bf47622b9da6', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Pieza del mes\n- Venue: Museo de Historia de Madrid\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Museo de Historia de Madrid, Calle de Fuencarral, 78, 28004 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-03-03 to 2026-03-31\n- Suggested visit duration: 30 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Across the galleries at Museo de Historia de Madrid, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Watch\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Watch one Madrid object get the full treatment, with crisp context notes, archival images, and a brisk 30 minute stop at the museum.", "long": "<p>Across the galleries at Museo de Historia de Madrid, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype. Pieza del mes keeps the scale tight and the focus sharp: one object, a small set of supporting documents, and clear wall text that favours evidence over grand claims. The result rewards slow looking, from paper fibres and tool marks to the civic stamps and handwritten numbers that usually get ignored in a crowded case.</p>\\n<p>The highlight in March is an albumen photograph by Jean Laurent that frames Madrid as a working city rather than a postcard. Stone façades read as surfaces with scars, shop signs pull the eye to street level, and a thin line of traffic hints at changing habits of movement. The print’s tonal range matters here, with deep shadows under balconies and a pale sky that leaves architecture to do the work.</p>\\n<p>One don’t-miss element is the side-by-side comparison with a wall-sized reproduction of Pedro Texeira’s 1656 map of Madrid, used as a visual anchor for street layout and naming. The pairing makes urban change legible without resorting to sweeping statements. A second don’t-miss is the magnification station, which brings out retouching on the negative, edge wear from handling, and the photographer’s numbering system along the margin.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits in plain sight: the verso details. Faint pencil notes, a collector’s mark, and a small paper repair turn the photograph into a travelled object with its own biography. Nearby context points beyond the case: León Gil de Palacio’s 1830 scale model of Madrid, seen in the museum’s rooms, helps translate the photograph’s flat planes into volumes, heights, and routes, with rooftops and courtyards snapping into place.</p>\\n<p>Running from 3 to 31 March 2026, the display fits a 30 minute circuit, including time to read the object label in full and return for a second look after the map comparison. Text is in Spanish with key terms clarified for non-specialists, and the lighting is tuned to protect the print while keeping surface gloss under control. A final caption calls attention to the pressure mark of an official seal impressed into the paper.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
