2026-01-23 14:35:41,336 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-ad15e23d-511e-49cc-a096-88d258a33c71', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Rilke y el arte español, Exhibition, Museo Nacional del Prado, Madrid\n- Venue: Museo Nacional del Prado\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Museo Nacional del Prado, Calle Ruiz de Alarcón, 23, 28014 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-11-17 to 2027-03-07\n- Suggested visit duration: 90 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: In the first rooms at Museo Nacional del Prado, close looking matters as objects and images do the work.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'See\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "See poems and paintings speak through manuscripts, postcards and Prado masterworks, connecting El Greco, Velázquez and Goya in 90 minutes.", "long": "<p>In the first rooms at Museo Nacional del Prado, close looking matters as objects and images do the work. The display tracks how Rainer Maria Rilke reads Spain through painting, and how Spanish art reshapes his language in notebooks, letters, and revised drafts. The museum context keeps attention on the act of seeing, a poem draft sits beside a painted hand, a sentence answers a stare, a margin note argues with a catalogue description.</p>\\n<p>A clear highlight is the group of original manuscripts and correspondence that records Rilke’s travel notes and his return to certain images, sometimes on the same day. Pages show crossings-out, sudden enjambments, and careful rephrasing, making the writing process visible rather than polished. Wall texts stay spare and factual, leaving room for the object itself, ink tone, paper weight, and the rhythm of a line.</p>\\n<p>Do not miss the dialogue with El Greco, anchored by <i>The Nobleman with his Hand on his Chest</i>. The painting’s compressed space and calm intensity sit near Rilke’s notes on portraiture, where he searches for an ethics of looking, not a mere description. A smaller cluster of devotional images sharpens the comparison, including Zurbarán’s <i>Agnus Dei</i>, where restraint and material precision echo the poet’s pared-back phrasing.</p>\\n<p>Do not miss the section built around Velázquez, with <i>Las Meninas</i> used as a test case for perspective, authorship, and the onlooker’s role. Rilke’s comments on mirrors and thresholds gain force when set against Velázquez’s painted light, and the route then turns to Goya, with <i>The Third of May 1808</i> marking a shift from contemplation to moral shock. A listening point adds a practical tool, recorded readings in German and Spanish, kept brief, allow attention to consonants, pauses, and breath without turning the galleries into a recital.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits in a modest vitrine of ephemera, a small set of postcards, a pared-down travel note, and an early Spanish printing of Rilke in translation, all easy to pass without slowing down. Rilke y el arte español runs at Museo Nacional del Prado from 17 November 2026 to 7 March 2027 and suits an unhurried 90-minute circuit.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
