2026-01-23 14:35:50,616 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-6f93dd42-b1ee-4c0d-bfc5-cfc7d7bb3c4f', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Pieza del mes\n- Venue: Museo de Historia de Madrid\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Museo de Historia de Madrid, Calle de Fuencarral, 78, 28004 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-03-03 to 2026-03-31\n- Suggested visit duration: 30 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Across the galleries at Museo de Historia de Madrid, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Watch\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Watch one Madrid object command attention through close looking, sharp context, and small archival turns, a focused 30 minute stop.", "long": "<p>Across the galleries at Museo de Historia de Madrid, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype. Pieza del mes keeps the frame tight: one object, a small cluster of supporting documents, and wall text that sticks to evidence. The slow reward comes through paper fibres, tool marks, stamps, and pencilled numbers that rarely earn attention in a busy room. Mounting, spacing, and lighting are treated as part of the reading, with surfaces kept calm so marks and edges stay legible.</p>\\n<p>The March highlight is an albumen photograph by Jean Laurent, printed with crisp edges and a restrained tonal scale. Madrid reads as a working city, not a postcard, with balcony shadows cutting across façades and shop signs pulling the gaze down to street level. A thin line of carts and foot traffic hints at routines under pressure from new transport and rebuilding. The print’s warm gloss, typical of albumen, catches the light in patches, so the angle of viewing matters as much as the caption.</p>\\n<p>One don’t-miss element is the side-by-side link to Pedro Texeira’s 1656 map of Madrid (shown as a large reproduction), used as a visual anchor for street names and alignments. The pairing makes shifts in routes and landmarks legible without sweeping claims, and it encourages a second look at where Laurent chooses to stand. A second don’t-miss is the magnification station, which brings out negative retouching, edge wear from handling, and the photographer’s numbering along the margin. A nearby municipal-style inventory card, with ink stamps and filing codes, adds an administrative voice to the image.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits on the back of the print. Faint pencil notes, a collector’s mark, and a small paper repair turn the photograph into an object with a travelled life, not just an image. The reverse also reveals pressure dents where the sheet once sat against a mount, a quiet record of storage and display habits. Nearby, a reference label points to León Gil de Palacio’s 1830 scale model of Madrid elsewhere in the museum, a useful way to translate flat planes into volumes, rooflines, and courtyards.</p>\\n<p>Running from 3 to 31 March 2026, the display suits a 30 minute circuit, including time to read the catalogue-style label and then look again after the map comparison. Text runs in Spanish, with key terms clarified in plain phrasing for non-specialists. Light levels stay low to protect the photograph while keeping surface sheen under control, and the caption calls out an impressed seal mark that leaves a shallow ridge in the paper. A small ruler graphic on the label sets the print’s dimensions at a glance.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 435)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
