tion name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'See\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "See poems and paintings speak through manuscripts, postcards and Prado masterworks, connecting El Greco, Velázquez and Goya in 90 minutes.", "long": "<p>In the first rooms at Museo Nacional del Prado, close looking matters as objects and images do the work. The display tracks how Rainer Maria Rilke reads Spain through painting, and how Spanish art reshapes his language in notebooks, letters, and revised drafts. The museum context keeps attention on the act of seeing, a poem draft sits beside a painted hand, a sentence answers a stare, a margin note argues with a catalogue description.</p>\\n<p>A clear highlight is the group of original manuscripts and correspondence that records Rilke’s travel notes and his return to certain images, sometimes on the same day. Pages show crossings-out, sudden enjambments, and careful rephrasing, making the writing process visible rather than polished. Wall texts stay spare and factual, leaving room for the object itself, ink tone, paper weight, and the rhythm of a line.</p>\\n<p>Do not miss the dialogue with El Greco, anchored by <i>The Nobleman with his Hand on his Chest</i>. The painting’s compressed space and calm intensity sit near Rilke’s notes on portraiture, where he searches for an ethics of looking, not a mere description. A smaller cluster of devotional images sharpens the comparison, including Zurbarán’s <i>Agnus Dei</i>, where restraint and material precision echo the poet’s pared-back phrasing.</p>\\n<p>Do not miss the section built around Velázquez, with <i>Las Meninas</i> used as a test case for perspective, authorship, and the onlooker’s role. Rilke’s comments on mirrors and thresholds gain force when set against Velázquez’s painted light, and the route then turns to Goya, with <i>The Third of May 1808</i> marking a shift from contemplation to moral shock. A listening point adds a practical tool, recorded readings in German and Spanish, kept brief, allow attention to consonants, pauses, and breath without turning the galleries into a recital.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits in a modest vitrine of ephemera, a small set of postcards, a pared-down travel note, and an early Spanish printing of Rilke in translation, all easy to pass without slowing down. Rilke y el arte español runs from 17 November 2026 to 7 March 2027 in Madrid and suits an unhurried 90-minute circuit.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
