2026-01-23 14:36:39,595 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-20a28b61-2212-49ef-a606-cf258e5bdfd7', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Exposición \'ESPERE SU TURNO\' de Riki Blanco, Exhibition, Central de diseño (Matadero), Madrid\n- Venue: Central de diseño (Matadero)\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Paseo de la Chopera, 14, 28045 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2025-12-15 to 2026-02-01\n- Suggested visit duration: 45 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Galleries at Central de diseño (Matadero) set out a clear route through materials, techniques and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Watch\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Watch Riki Blanco turn queues into sharp drawings, prints and looping animations at Matadero Madrid, a tight 45-minute circuit.", "long": "<p>Galleries at Central de diseño (Matadero) set out a clear route through materials, techniques and context. The title, “Espere su turno” (wait your turn), frames a compact survey of Riki Blanco’s graphic thinking, where a simple act of waiting becomes a system of rules, symbols and small rebellions. Madrid’s former industrial halls keep the tone plain and direct, letting paper, ink and timing do the work.</p>\\n<p>Blanco’s line cuts quickly from joke to critique. Original ink drawings pin down queue etiquette, authority and impatience with minimal marks, then push the same ideas into print and motion. A cluster of silkscreen posters uses stark typography and numbered forms to mimic public signage. Nearby, a set of storyboard panels maps how a gag lands across frames, insisting that timing is as important as the image.</p>\\n<p>Highlight: a dense wall of sequential drawings that reads like a silent comic, moving from calm order to quiet sabotage in a handful of strokes. Do not miss the looping animation station, where short clips turn waiting-room rituals into repeating choreography. Do not miss the vitrine of working materials, including marked-up proofs and colour tests that show decisions made under constraint.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits in a side section devoted to throwaway formats, queue tickets, stamps, marginal notes and small-format prints that rarely survive everyday use. Here, Blanco treats bureaucracy as raw material, re-cutting it into visual punchlines and sharp observations. The show also nods to his broader practice across editorial illustration and graphic narratives, without turning the room into a career timeline.</p>\\n<p>Running from 15 December 2025 to 1 February 2026 at Central de diseño (Matadero) in Madrid, Spain, the installation suits a focused 45-minute visit. Sightlines stay open, but the densest rewards come from close reading of captions, corrections and repeated motifs across the drawings, posters and animated loops.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 304)\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
