2026-01-23 14:37:06,018 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-38d8818d-67c4-439b-9fcf-78d41beb3bd5', 'json_data': {'input': "Translate the following Divento temporary exhibition content.\n\nRules (follow exactly):\n- Return ONLY a JSON object matching the provided schema.\n- Do not add citations, links, or URLs.\n- Avoid em/en dash characters (— or –); rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Keep all HTML tags intact in 'long' and return valid HTML.\n- Do NOT add extra blank lines/newlines.\n- For 'short': maximum 164 characters in the target language, keep natural phrasing.\n- For 'name': translate only what should be translated; keep proper nouns/titles as appropriate.\n- For zh-CN: translate ALL prose into Simplified Chinese; Latin script is allowed ONLY for proper nouns and official artwork/series titles.\n\nEnglish inputs:\n- name_en: Exposición Ómnibus. El futuro se dibuja aquí, Exhibition, Casa del Lector, Madrid: 20 November 2025-1 February 2026\n- short_en: Chart how drawings, comics and sound scripts imagine tomorrow at Casa del Lector in Madrid, in a focused 60-minute circuit.\nlong_en_html:\n<p>Rooms at Casa del Lector map the show’s themes through objects, images, sound and text. Exposición Ómnibus. El futuro se dibuja aquí is running in Madrid, Spain, from 20 November 2025 to 1 February 2026, and it keeps the pace tight, around 60 minutes. The route moves between reading, looking and listening, treating the page as a site for invention and argument rather than decoration. An “ómnibus” logic runs through the display, with short forms, serial fragments and compiled sequences sitting side by side.</p><p>Early sections foreground process. Pencil thumbnails sit beside inked storyboard panels, colour tests and printer’s proofs, so decisions stay visible, cut lines, taped joins and correction fluid included. A sequence of annotated layouts tracks how a single scene shifts through framing and rhythm, while a bank of short texts names the tools, nibs, brushes and software settings that shape the final mark. A small vitrine gathers paper stocks, staples and binding thread, connecting a finished book to its most ordinary parts.</p><p>Highlight: a wall-length collaborative comic strip that grows panel by panel across the rooms, stitching everyday Madrid details into speculative situations. Don’t miss the risograph zine rack, where small-run pamphlets, fold-outs and stapled mini comics form a quick survey of current graphic self-publishing, complete with colophon notes, print runs and smudged ink edges. Don’t miss the sound kiosks either, which pair spoken scripts with projected drawings, letting timing and breath drive the images, with pauses marked as blank frames and repeated lines treated as visual loops.</p><p>Public transport acts as a quiet organising metaphor. Route maps, ticket stubs and timetable graphics appear as source material, then re-emerge as diagrams for imagined cities and alternative futures. Posters and mock book covers test how typography carries tone, from blocky headlines to tight footnotes, and a set of flipbooks turns gesture into motion, one frame at a time, under steady overhead light. Several pages stay unbound on light tables, so gutters, crop marks and registration errors remain part of the reading.</p><p>Hidden gem: a low drawer of discarded drafts, margins and rejected captions, kept deliberately rough, with notes that argue with themselves. It sits near a small table of materials, acetate sheets, tracing paper, marker pens and binding thread, and nearby pinboards hold thumbnail grids, thumbnail grids crossed out, and replacement captions scribbled on receipts, showing how narrative control often depends on mundane paper scraps.</p>\n", 'max_output_tokens': 9000, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_translation_bundle', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'fr': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'es': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'it': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'ru': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'zh-CN': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}}, 'required': ['fr', 'es', 'it', 'ru', 'zh-CN']}}}}}
