2026-01-23 14:38:17,513 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-1f3e2590-c64d-461c-b206-fe412a19474d', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Alberto Greco Viva el arte vivo, Exhibition, Museo Reina Sofía, Madrid\n- Venue: Museo Reina Sofía\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Calle Santa Isabel, 52, 28012 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-02-11 to 2026-06-08\n- Suggested visit duration: 90 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Inside the galleries at Museo Reina Sofía, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Compare\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Compare Greco’s Vivo-Dito actions with drawings, manifestos and street documentation, then track how art slips into daily life.", "long": "<p>Inside the galleries at Museo Reina Sofía, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context. Alberto Greco’s practice lands in Madrid with a tight focus on gesture, risk and attention, and it runs from 11 February to 8 June 2026. Painting, writing, photography and street action sit side by side, with wall texts that stay close to what Greco did and how it circulated.</p>\\n<p>The first rooms set out the tools of arte vivo: ink, stamp, camera, tape, and the quick line that claims a moment. A highlight is the serial presentation of Vivo-Dito material, where Greco’s finger becomes a pointer and a signature, and everyday scenes turn into declared works. Do not miss the original manifestos and typed statements, including versions of the Manifiesto del Arte Vivo, their crossings-out and emphatic underlining keeping the thinking in motion.</p>\\n<p>Photographs and printed matter carry the actions forward. Contact sheets, press cuttings and posters map how an event survives after it disappears, and how authorship shifts between artist, subject and witness. Do not miss the documentation that tracks Greco’s interventions in public space, where a chalk circle, a handwritten label or a stamped mark recalibrates a street corner, a passer-by, a shop window.</p>\\n<p>Drawings and works on paper slow the pace without softening the edge. Lines interrupt faces, bodies and objects; notes act as instructions rather than descriptions. Several small-scale sheets hold the same urgency as the street actions, and their economy of means keeps attention on decision and timing. The installation also brings in letters and administrative documents that show negotiation, refusal and strategy around exhibition making.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits in a modest vitrine of postcards, invitations and annotated ephemera, where a casual salutation or address line turns into a proposal for action. Allow about 90 minutes to take in the full arc, from manifesto to residue, and to follow the repeated question of what counts as a work when the world is treated as the surface. Film excerpts and audio fragments add cadence to the rooms, keeping the emphasis on encounter rather than object.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 348)\n- long includes address wording\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
