2026-01-23 14:38:26,624 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-18df414f-929b-4357-a5c7-7bf27deab07f', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Madrid Colecciona. 50 colecciones de arte contemporáneo, Exhibition, CentroCentro, Madrid\n- Venue: CentroCentro\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Plaza de Cibeles, 1, 28014 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-02-26 to 2026-09-06\n- Suggested visit duration: 90 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Inside the galleries at CentroCentro, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Listen\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Listen to Madrid’s collectors through paintings, sculpture and archive notes at CentroCentro, a 90-minute circuit of contemporary art.", "long": "<p>Inside the galleries at CentroCentro, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context. Madrid Colecciona draws on 50 contemporary art collections and treats each loan as evidence of a choice, a relationship, a risk. Painting meets sculpture, photography interrupts drawing, and small documentary groupings trace how works pass from studio to private walls, offices, storage racks and, at times, public programmes.</p>\\n\\n<p>Attention stays on objects and provenance rather than a single narrative. Antoni Tàpies, Miquel Barceló and Juan Muñoz anchor several rooms with materially insistent works, while other sections turn to artists’ books, multiples and works on paper where scale sharpens ideas. Labels cite acquisition years and prior displays, and vitrines hold catalogues, invitation cards, press clippings and correspondence. Material choices stay legible, bronze, resin, charcoal, collage, inkjet print, and installation decisions push close looking at joints, seams and repairs.</p>\\n\\n<p>Highlight: a tightly edited sequence on sculptural thinking, where maquettes, casts and finished pieces sit in proximity to show how weight, balance and surface change across iterations. A grouping around interior space and thresholds brings Cristina Iglesias into dialogue with quieter, room-scaled works, and the conversation between object and architecture becomes the point rather than a backdrop.</p>\\n\\n<p>Do not miss: the photographic wall that moves from staged portraiture to documentary series, then to conceptual image making, with works by Joan Fontcuberta and others arranged to expose repetition, cropping and caption strategies. Do not miss: the screening corner for time-based work, where short films and single-channel videos slow the tempo and concentrate attention on sound, subtitles and cuts, with benches placed close enough to hear incidental noise and breath.</p>\\n\\n<p>Hidden gem: a small case of ephemera and marginalia, including handwritten checklists, shipping labels, condition notes and annotated floorplans that show how collecting relies on logistics as much as taste. Several panels also map networks between private holdings and institutional loans, indicating how a single work can circulate through loans, publications and conservation. The exhibition runs in Madrid, Spain, from 26 February 2026 to 6 September 2026, and a 90 minute visit suits the full circuit.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 347)\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
