2026-01-23 14:39:07,909 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-026980d4-2d4d-4cea-8a8c-6ffe12f36969', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Andrea Canepa Fardo, Exhibition, Museo Reina Sofía, Madrid\n- Venue: Museo Reina Sofía\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Calle Santa Isabel, 52, 28012 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2026-01-13 to 2027-01-01\n- Suggested visit duration: 45-60 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: A sequence of rooms at Museo Reina Sofía grounds the show in specific works and practical context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Unpick\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Unpick Andrea Canepa’s charged materials and quiet sound cues at Museo Reina Sofía, a tight 45 to 60 minutes with sharp turns and lingering aftertaste.", "long": "<p>A sequence of rooms at Museo Reina Sofía grounds the show in specific works and practical context. In Madrid, Andrea Canepa tests how an artwork carries weight, literally in bundled matter and figuratively in memory, labour, and the routes objects take through hands. Runs from 13 January 2026 to 1 January 2027, the installation rewards a steady pace and close looking across 45 to 60 minutes.</p>\\n<p>The entry sets a restrained tempo: paper, fabric, and wood meet disciplined light and clear sightlines. A central object, a tightly wrapped hessian load titled <i>Fardo</i>, anchors the first room and acts as a hinge for everything that follows. Nearby, a sequence of graphite rubbings lifts texture from everyday surfaces, turning scuffs and grain into a kind of evidence.</p>\\n<p>A highlight arrives in the sound room, where a four-channel audio work uses breath, steps, and clipped phrases to pull attention away from the walls and into the body. One don’t-miss element is the set of annotated notebooks under glass, dense with measurements, diagrams, and crossed-out decisions that clarify how the larger forms are built. Another don’t-miss element sits opposite: a small projection of hand movements, slowed to near stillness, that makes simple actions read as ritual.</p>\\n<p>Material choices keep doing the talking. Rope bites into cloth, staples hold seams, and rough timber frames refuse to disappear behind the idea of “finish”. The show’s internal logic becomes clearest in the transition corridor, where contact sheets and working photographs trace the same object through different rooms and lighting conditions, insisting on repetition as method rather than decoration.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem waits near the end, an unassuming wall vitrine of letters, packing slips, and a folded map marked with pencilled routes. It reads like studio debris, yet it sharpens the exhibition’s stakes by tying each bundle and marking to a chain of handling and exchange. Notes in the margins keep changing the reading of the whole.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 320)\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
