2026-01-23 14:40:28,396 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-3beb9644-7b3a-44d6-92c8-49b111ecc995', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Oliver Laxe HU/هُوَ. Bailad como si nadie os viera, Exhibition, Museo Reina Sofía, Madrid\n- Venue: Museo Reina Sofía\n- City: Madrid\n- Country: Spain\n- Address: Calle Santa Isabel, 52, 28012 Madrid, Spain\n- Dates (ISO): 2025-12-17 to 2026-04-20\n- Suggested visit duration: 45-60 minutes\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Labels at Museo Reina Sofía keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Map\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Map Laxe’s route through notebooks, film clips and field recordings, then pause with a multi-screen montage and a hushed sound room.", "long": "<p>Labels at Museo Reina Sofía keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. Running in Madrid from 17 December 2025 to 20 April 2026, Oliver Laxe HU/هُوَ. Bailad como si nadie os viera sets cinema beside working materials: annotated scripts, call sheets, contact sheets, and camera tests that show how scenes are built, not merely shown. The layout moves between dark rooms and bright vitrines, so eyes adjust from projection glow to paper grain. Allow 45 to 60 minutes to move between screens, documents, and a compact listening area where sound carries as much weight as image.</p>\\n<p>Highlight: a central, darkened room presents HU/هُوَ as a spatial edit, with Arabic text, subtitles, and repeated gestures that treat the pronoun “he” as both character and camera position. Cuts land on hands, smoke, stone, and cloth, and the installation’s pacing makes attention shift from narrative to rhythm, breath, and off-screen space. A tight loop of close-ups, held longer than expected, turns small motions into structure, and the room’s seating encourages staying through several cycles.</p>\\n<p>Don’t miss element one, a multi-screen sequence that tracks the ascent and detours of <em>Mimosas</em> (2016), pairing rugged landscape shots with production stills and a marked-up shooting plan. Overhead notes pin timings to light changes, and a strip of contact prints shows how framing tightens take by take. Don’t miss element two, a sound-focused passage built from field recordings and dialogue fragments tied to <em>O que arde</em> (2019), where crackle, wind, and distant voices act as scene partners rather than background; listening reveals how silence is cut and paced like dialogue.</p>\\n<p>Beyond the projections, vitrines gather Laxe’s working trail across <em>Todos vós sodes capitáns</em> (2010), <em>Mimosas</em>, and <em>O que arde</em>: storyboard strips, colour references, rehearsal notes, and correspondence that records negotiations with locations and non-professional performers. A small wall grouping of production photographs traces how the same shot changes through lens choice, distance, and time of day, making craft decisions legible at a glance. Paper edits sit beside stills, with taped joins and crossing-outs that keep uncertainty visible.</p>\\n<p>Hidden gem: a modest folder of hand-drawn route maps and timing diagrams, smudged with pencil and coffee rings, sits near a set of discarded subtitle drafts, revealing how meaning shifts through translation. A vitrine of alternate title cards and translated phrases shows changes in tone from Arabic to Spanish and back again. Short, scheduled projections of rushes run alongside the main installation, and a bench near the listening area supports slower looking as the room’s acoustics change with each edit.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 426)\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
